"1279":"1279","1289":"1289","1255":"1255","1254":"1254","about 1255":"circa 1255","1318":"1318","Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Markham Nottinghamshire England":"Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"en":{"about 1255–1301":"about 1255–1301","1252–1305":"1252–1305","1254–1318":"1254–1318","1255–1301":"1255–1301","1255–1295":"1255–1295","1279–Female":"1279–Deceased","1283–Male":"1283–Deceased","1230–1289":"1230–1289","1220–1274":"1220–1274","about 1283":"about 1283","24 June 1279":"24 June 1279","1220":"1220","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1252":"1252","1295":"1295","1283":"1283","1290":"1290","1305":"1305","1259":"1259","1301":"1301","1279":"1279","1289":"1289","1255":"1255","1254":"1254","about 1255":"about 1255","1318":"1318","Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Markham Nottinghamshire England":"Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Markham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Markham Clinton or East Markham (Nottinghamshire). The placename derives from Old English <i>mearc</i> ‘mark, boundary’ + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’ or <i>hamm</i> ‘water meadow’.","Irish: English surname used as an equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Marcacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Marcachán</i>’, a diminutive of <i>Marcach</i> ‘horseman, rider’ (see   Markey  ). This was originally a Galway surname but is now found mainly in Clare, sometimes translated into English as   Ryder  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Markey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Donal, Donovan, Fergal.","Irish (Monaghan): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Marcaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Marcach</i>’, a name meaning ‘horseman, knight’, from <i>marc</i> ‘horse’. Compare   Markham   2.","English: apparently from a placename meaning ‘boundary river’ in Old or Middle English, but no such place has been identified."]},{"name":"Markum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Markham  ."]},{"name":"Marcum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Markham  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],